#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:133
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are essentially three sources of documentation on a Linux system: manual\n"
"pages, info pages, and application-bundled documentation in\n"
"<path>/usr/share/doc</path>. In this section, we'll explore each of these\n"
"sources before looking \"outside the box\" for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:142
#, no-wrap
msgid "Manual pages"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:146
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Manual pages, or \"man pages\", are the classic form of UNIX and Linux reference\n"
"documentation. Ideally, you can look up the man page for any command,\n"
"configuration file, or library routine. In practice, Linux is free software,\n"
"and some pages haven't been written or are showing their age. Nonetheless, man\n"
"pages are the first place to look when you need help.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:154
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To access a man page, simply type <c>man</c> followed by your topic of inquiry.\n"
"A pager will be started, so you will need to press <c>q</c> when you're done\n"
"reading. For example, to look up information about the <c>ls</c> command, you\n"
"would type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:160
#, no-wrap
msgid "Searching in man page"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:161
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>man ls</i>\n"
msgstr ""

