#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:243
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Some topics exist in more than one section. To demonstrate this, let's use the\n"
"<c>whatis</c> command, which shows all the available man pages for a topic:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:247
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using whatis command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:248
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>whatis printf</i>\n"
"printf               (1)  - format and print data\n"
"printf               (3)  - formatted output conversion\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:254
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this case, <c>man printf</c> would default to the page in section 1 (\"User\n"
"Programs\"). If we were writing a C program, we might be more interested in the\n"
"page from section 3 (\"Library functions\"). You can call up a man page from a\n"
"certain section by specifying it on the command line, so to ask for\n"
"<e>printf(3)</e>, we would type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:261
#, no-wrap
msgid "Specifying section in man command"
