#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:393
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There is a final source for help within your Linux system. Many programs are\n"
"shipped with additional documentation in other formats: text, PDF, PostScript,\n"
"HTML, to name a few. Take a look in <path>usr/share/doc</path> (or\n"
"<path>/usr/doc</path> on older systems). You'll find a long list of\n"
"directories, each of which came with a certain application on your system.\n"
"Searching through this documentation can often reveal some gems that aren't\n"
"available as man pages or info pages, such as tutorials or additional technical\n"
"documentation. A quick check reveals there's a lot of reading material\n"
"available:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:404
#, no-wrap
msgid "/usr/share/doc/"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:405
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>cd /usr/share/doc</i>\n"
"$ <i>find . -type f | wc -l</i>\n"
"7582\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:411
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Whew! Your homework this evening is to read just half (3791) of those\n"
"documents. Expect a quiz tomorrow. ;-)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:418
#, no-wrap
msgid "The Linux Documentation Project"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:422
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In addition to system documentation, there are a number of excellent Linux\n"
"resources on the Internet. The <uri link=\"http://www.tldp.org/\">Linux\n"
"Documentation Project</uri> is a group of volunteers who are working on putting\n"
"together the complete set of free Linux documentation. This project exists to\n"
"consolidate various pieces of Linux documentation into a location that is easy\n"
"to search and use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:433
#, no-wrap
msgid "An LDP overview"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:437
#, no-wrap
msgid "The LDP is made up of the following areas:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:442
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Guides - longer, more in-depth books, such as <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://www.tldp.org/LDP/lpg/index.html\">The Linux Programmer's\n"
"    Guide</uri>\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:447
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    HOWTOs - subject-specific help, such as the <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://www.tldp.org/HOWTO/DSL-HOWTO/index.html\">DSL HOWTO</uri>\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:451
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    FAQs - Frequently Asked Questions with answers, such as the <uri\n"
"    link=\"http://www.tldp.org/FAQ/faqs/BLFAQ\">Brief Linux FAQ</uri>\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:455
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Man pages - help on individual commands (these are the same manual pages\n"
"    you get on your Linux system when you use the <c>man</c> command).\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:461
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you aren't sure which section to peruse, you can take advantage of the\n"
"search box, which allows you to find things by topic.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:466
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The LDP additionally provides a list of Links and Resources such as <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.tldp.org/LDP/LG/current/\">Linux Gazette</uri> (see links in\n"
"<uri link=\"#resources\">Resources</uri>) and <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.tldp.org/linuxfocus/index.html\">LinuxFocus</uri>, as well\n"
"links to mailing lists and news archives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:476
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mailing lists"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:480
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Mailing lists provide probably the most important point of collaboration for\n"
"Linux developers. Often projects are developed by contributors who live far\n"
"apart, possibly even on opposite sides of the globe. Mailing lists provide a\n"
"method for each developer on a project to contact all the others, and to hold\n"
"group discussions via e-mail. One of the most famous development mailing lists\n"
"is the <uri link=\"http://www.tux.org/lkml/\">Linux Kernel Mailing List</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:491
#, no-wrap
msgid "More about mailing lists"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:495
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In addition to development, mailing lists can provide a method for asking\n"
"questions and receiving answers from knowledgeable developers, or even other\n"
"users. For example, individual distributions often provide mailing lists for\n"
"newcomers. You can check your distribution's Web site for information on the\n"
"mailing lists it provides.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:503
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you took the time to read the LKML FAQ at the link on the previous panel,\n"
"you might have noticed that mailing list subscribers often don't take kindly to\n"
"questions being asked repeatedly. It's always wise to search the archives for a\n"
"given mailing list before writing your question. Chances are, it will save you\n"
"time, too!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:513
#, no-wrap
msgid "Newsgroups"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:517
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Internet \"newsgroups\" are similar to mailing lists, but are based on a protocol\n"
"called NNTP (\"Network News Transfer Protocol\") instead of e-mail. To\n"
"participate, you need to use an NNTP client such as <c>slrn</c> or <c>pan</c>.\n"
"The primary advantage is that you only take part in the discussion when you\n"
"want, instead of having it continually arrive in your inbox. :-)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:525
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The newsgroups of primary interest start with comp.os.linux. You can browse the\n"
"<uri link=\"http://www.tldp.org/links/#ng\">list on the LDP site</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:530
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As with mailing lists, newsgroup discussion is often archived. A popular\n"
"newsgroup archiving site is <uri\n"
"link=\"http://groups.google.com/googlegroups/deja_announcement.html\">Deja\n"
"News</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

