#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:610
#, no-wrap
msgid "The Linux permissions model"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:612
#, no-wrap
msgid "One user, one group"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:616
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this section, we'll take a look at the Linux permissions and ownership\n"
"model. We've already seen that every file is owned by one user and one group.\n"
"This is the very core of the permissions model in Linux. You can view the user\n"
"and group of a file in a <c>ls -l</c> listing:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:622
#, no-wrap
msgid "Listing files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:623
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:646
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:673
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ls -l /bin/bash</i>\n"
"-rwxr-xr-x    1 root     wheel      430540 Dec 23 18:27 /bin/bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:628
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this particular example, the <path>/bin/bash</path> executable is owned by\n"
"root and is in the wheel group. The Linux permissions model works by allowing\n"
"three independent levels of permission to be set for each filesystem object --\n"
"those for the file's owner, the file's group, and all other users.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:637
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding \"ls -l\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:641
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's take a look at our <c>ls -l</c> output and inspect the first column of\n"
"the listing:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:645
#, no-wrap
msgid "Inspecting ls -l command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:651
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This first field <e>-rwxr-xr-</e> contains a symbolic representation of this\n"
"particular files' permissions. The first character (-) in this field specifies\n"
"the type of this file, which in this case is a regular file. Other possible\n"
"first characters:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:657
#, no-wrap
msgid "First characters"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:658
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"'d' directory\n"
"'l' symbolic link\n"
"'c' character special device \n"
"'b' block special device\n"
"'p' fifo\n"
"'s' socket\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:669
#, no-wrap
msgid "Three triplets"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:672
#, no-wrap
msgid "ls -l /bin/bash"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:678
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The rest of the field consists of three character triplets. The first triplet\n"
"represents permissions for the owner of the file, the second represents\n"
"permissions for the file's group, and the third represents permissions for all\n"
"other users:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:684
#, no-wrap
msgid "Triplets in ls -l command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:685
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\"rwx\"\n"
"\"r-x\"\n"
"\"r-x\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:691
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Above, the r means that reading (looking at the data in the file) is allowed,\n"
"the w means that writing (modifying the file, as well as deletion) is allowed,\n"
"and the x means that \"execute\" (running the program) is allowed. Putting\n"
"together all this information, we can see that everyone is able to read the\n"
"contents of and execute this file, but only the owner (root) is allowed to\n"
"modify this file in any way. So, while normal users can copy this file, only\n"
"root is allowed to update it or delete it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:703
#, no-wrap
msgid "Who am I?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:707
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Before we take a look at how to change the user and group ownership of a file,\n"
"let's first take a look at how to learn your current user id and group\n"
"membership. Unless you've used the <c>su</c> command recently, your current\n"
"user id is the one you used to log in to the system. If you use <c>su</c>\n"
"frequently, however, you may not remember your current effective user id. To\n"
"view it, type <c>whoami</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:715
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using whoami command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:716
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>whoami</i>\n"
"root\n"
"# <i>su drobbins</i>\n"
"$ <i>whoami</i>\n"
"drobbins\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:726
#, no-wrap
msgid "What groups am I in?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:730
#, no-wrap
msgid "To see what groups you belong to, use the <c>groups</c> command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:733
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using groups command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:734
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>groups</i>\n"
"drobbins wheel audio\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:739
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In the above example, I'm a member of the drobbins, wheel, and audio groups.\n"
"If you want to see what groups other user(s) are in, specify their usernames as\n"
"arguments:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:744
#, no-wrap
msgid "Specifying user argument"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:745
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>groups root daemon</i>\n"
"root : root bin daemon sys adm disk wheel floppy dialout tape video\n"
"daemon : daemon bin adm\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:753
#, no-wrap
msgid "Changing user and group ownership"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:757
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To change the owner or group of a file or other filesystem object, use\n"
"<c>chown</c> or <c>chgrp</c>, respectively. Each of these commands takes a name\n"
"followed by one or more filenames.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:762
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using chown and chgrp commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:763
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>chown root /etc/passwd</i>\n"
"# <i>chgrp wheel /etc/passwd</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:768
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can also set the owner and group simultaneously with an alternate form of\n"
"the <c>chown</c> command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:772
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting owner and group simultaneously"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:773
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>chown root:wheel /etc/passwd</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:777
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You may not use <c>chown</c> unless you are the superuser, but <c>chgrp</c> can\n"
"be used by anyone to change the group ownership of a file to a group to which\n"
"they belong.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:785
#, no-wrap
msgid "Recursive ownership changes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:789
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Both <c>chown</c> and <c>chgrp</c> have a -R option that can be used to tell\n"
"them to recursively apply ownership and group changes to an entire directory\n"
"tree. For example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:794
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using chown and chgrp with -R option"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:795
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>chown -R drobbins /home/drobbins</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:801
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing chmod"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:805
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<c>chown</c> and <c>chgrp</c> can be used to change the owner and group of a\n"
"filesystem object, but another program -- called <c>chmod</c> -- is used to\n"
"change the rwx permissions that we can see in an <c>ls -l</c> listing.\n"
"<c>chmod</c> takes two or more arguments: a \"mode\", describing how the\n"
"permissions should be changed, followed by a file or list of files that should\n"
"be affected:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:813
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding x permission with chmod"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:814
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>chmod +x scriptfile.sh</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:818
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In the above example, our \"mode\" is +x. As you might guess, a +x mode tells\n"
"<c>chmod</c> to make this particular file executable for both the user and\n"
"group and for anyone else.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:824
#, no-wrap
msgid "If we wanted to remove all execute permissions of a file, we'd do this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:827
#, no-wrap
msgid "Removing x permission with chmod"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:828
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>chmod -x scriptfile.sh</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:834
#, no-wrap
msgid "User/group/other granularity"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:838
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So far, our <c>chmod</c> examples have affected permissions for all three\n"
"triplets -- the user, the group, and all others. Often, it's handy to modify\n"
"only one or two triplets at a time. To do this, simply specify the symbolic\n"
"character for the particular triplets you'd like to modify before the + or -\n"
"sign. Use u for the \"user\" triplet, g for the \"group\" triplet, and o for the\n"
"\"other/everyone\" triplet:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:846
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using triplets"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:847
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>chmod go-w scriptfile.sh</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:851
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We just removed write permissions for the group and all other users, but left\n"
"\"owner\" permissions untouched.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:858
#, no-wrap
msgid "Resetting permissions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:862
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In addition to flipping permission bits on and off, we can also reset them\n"
"altogether. By using the = operator, we can tell <c>chmod</c> that we want the\n"
"specified permissions and no others:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:867
#, no-wrap
msgid "Flipping permission bits"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:868
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>chmod =rx scriptfile.sh</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:872
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Above, we just set all \"read\" and \"execute\" bits, and unset all \"write\" bits.\n"
"If you just want to reset a particular triplet, you can specify the symbolic\n"
"name for the triplet before the = as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:877
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reseting triplet"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:878
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>chmod u=rx scriptfile.sh</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:884
#, no-wrap
msgid "Numeric modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:888
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Up until now, we've used what are called symbolic modes to specify permission\n"
"changes to <c>chmod</c>. However, there's another common way of specifying\n"
"permissions: using a 4-digit octal number. Using this syntax, called numeric\n"
"permissions syntax, each digit represents a permissions triplet. For example,\n"
"in 1777, the 777 sets the \"owner\", \"group\", and \"other\" flags that we've been\n"
"discussing in this section. The 1 is used to set the special permissions bits,\n"
"which we'll cover later (see \"<uri\n"
"link=\"https://www6.software.ibm.com/developerworks/education/l-lpir23/l-lpir23-3-23.html\">The\n"
"elusive first digit</uri>\" at the end of this section). This chart shows how\n"
"the second through fourth digits (777) are interpreted:\n"
msgstr ""

