#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:942
#, no-wrap
msgid "Numeric permission syntax"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:946
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Numeric permission syntax is especially useful when you need to specify all\n"
"permissions for a file, such as in the following example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:950
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding numeric permission"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:951
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>chmod 0755 scriptfile.sh</i>\n"
"$ <i>ls -l scriptfile.sh</i>\n"
"-rwxr-xr-x    1 drobbins drobbins        0 Jan  9 17:44 scriptfile.sh\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:957
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this example, we used a mode of 0755, which expands to a complete\n"
"permissions setting of -rwxr-xr-x.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:964
#, no-wrap
msgid "The umask"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:968
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When a process creates a new file, it specifies the permissions that it would\n"
"like the new file to have. Often, the mode requested is 0666 (readable and\n"
"writable by everyone), which is more permissive that we would like.\n"
"Fortunately, Linux consults something called a \"umask\" whenever a new file is\n"
"created. The system uses the umask value to reduce the originally specified\n"
"permissions to something more reasonable and secure. You can view your current\n"
"umask setting by typing umask at the command line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:977
#, no-wrap
msgid "Viewing current umask"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:978
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>umask</i>\n"
"0022\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:983
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"On Linux systems, the umask normally defaults to 0022, which allows others to\n"
"read your new files (if they can get to them) but not modify them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:988
#, no-wrap
msgid "To make new files more secure by default, you can change the umask setting:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:991
#, no-wrap
msgid "Changing umask setting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:992
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>umask 0077</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:996
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This umask will make sure that the group and others will have absolutely no\n"
"permissions for any newly created files. So, how does the umask work? Unlike\n"
"\"regular\" permissions on files, the umask specifies which permissions should be\n"
"turned off. Let's consult our mode-to-digit mapping table so that we can\n"
"understand what a umask of 0077 means:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1043
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Using our table, the last three digits of 0077 expand to ---rwxrwx. Now,\n"
"remember that the <c>umask</c> tells the system which permissions to disable.\n"
"Putting two and two together, we can see that all \"group\" and \"other\"\n"
"permissions will be turned off, while \"user\" permissions will remain untouched.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1052
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing suid and sgid"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1056
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When you initially log in, a new shell process is started. You already know\n"
"that, but you may not know that this new shell process (typically bash) runs\n"
"using your user id. As such, the bash program can access all files and\n"
"directories that you own. In fact, we as users are totally dependent on other\n"
"programs to perform operations on our behalf. Because the programs you start\n"
"inherit your user id, they cannot access any filesystem objects for which you\n"
"haven't been granted access.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1066
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For example, the passwd file cannot be changed by normal users directly,\n"
"because the \"write\" flag is off for every user except root:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1070
#, no-wrap
msgid "ls -l /etc/passwd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1071
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ls -l /etc/passwd</i>\n"
"-rw-r--r--    1 root     wheel        1355 Nov  1 21:16 /etc/passwd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1076
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, normal users do need to be able to modify /etc/passwd (at least\n"
"indirectly) whenever they need to change their password. But, if the user is\n"
"unable to modify this file, how exactly does this work?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><th>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1084
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1259
#, no-wrap
msgid "suid"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1088
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Thankfully, the Linux permissions model has two special bits called <c>suid</c>\n"
"and <c>sgid</c>. When an executable program has the <c>suid</c> bit set, it\n"
"will run on behalf of the owner of the executable, rather than on behalf of the\n"
"person who started the program.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1095
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, back to the <path>/etc/passwd</path> problem. If we take a look at the\n"
"<c>passwd</c> executable, we can see that it's owned by root:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1099
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking owner of /usr/bin/passwd file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1100
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ls -l /usr/bin/passwd</i>\n"
"-rwsr-xr-x    1 root     wheel       17588 Sep 24 00:53 /usr/bin/passwd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1105
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You'll also note that in place of an x in the user's permission triplet,\n"
"there's an s. This indicates that, for this particular program, the <c>suid</c>\n"
"and executable bits are set. Because of this, when <c>passwd</c> runs, it will\n"
"execute on behalf of the root user (with full superuser access) rather than\n"
"that of the user who ran it. And because <c>passwd</c> runs with root access,\n"
"it's able to modify the <path>/etc/passwd</path> file with no problem.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1116
#, no-wrap
msgid "suid/sgid caveats"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1120
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We've seen how <c>suid</c> works, and <c>sgid</c> works in a similar way. It\n"
"allows programs to inherit the group ownership of the program rather than that\n"
"of the current user.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1126
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Here's some miscellaneous yet important information about <c>suid</c> and\n"
"<c>sgid</c>. First, <c>suid</c> and <c>sgid</c> bits occupy the same space as\n"
"the x bits in a ls -l listing. If the x bit is also set, the respective bits\n"
"will show up as s (lowercase). However, if the x bit is not set, it will show\n"
"up as a S (uppercase).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Another important note: suid and sgid come in handy in many circumstances, but\n"
"improper use of these bits can allow the security of a system to be breached.\n"
"It's best to have as few suid programs as possible. The passwd command is one\n"
"of the few that must be suid.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1143
#, no-wrap
msgid "Changing suid and sgid"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1147
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Setting and removing the <c>suid</c> and <c>sgid</c> bits is fairly\n"
"straightforward. Here, we set the suid bit:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1151
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting suid bit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1152
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>chmod u+s /usr/bin/myapp</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1156
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"And here, we remove the <c>sgid</c> bit from a directory. We'll see how the\n"
"<c>sgid</c> bit affects directories in just a few panels:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1160
#, no-wrap
msgid "Removing sgid bit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1161
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>chmod g-s /home/drobbins</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1167
#, no-wrap
msgid "Permissions and directories"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1171
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So far, we've been looking at permissions from the perspective of regular\n"
"files. When it comes to directories, things are a bit different. Directories\n"
"use the same permissions flags, but they are interpreted to mean slightly\n"
"different things.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1178
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For a directory, if the \"read\" flag is set, you may list the contents of the\n"
"directory; \"write\" means you may create files in the directory; and \"execute\"\n"
"means you may enter the directory and access any sub-directories inside.\n"
"Without the \"execute\" flag, the filesystem objects inside a directory aren't\n"
"accessible. Without a \"read\" flag, the filesystem objects inside a directory\n"
"aren't viewable, but objects inside the directory can still be accessed as long\n"
"as someone knows the full path to the object on disk.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1190
#, no-wrap
msgid "Directories and sgid"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1194
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"And, if a directory has the \"sgid\" flag enabled, any filesystem objects created\n"
"inside it will inherit the group of the directory. This particular feature\n"
"comes in handy when you need to create a directory tree to be used by a group\n"
"of people that all belong to the same group. Simply do this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1200
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating directory for a group of people"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1201
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>mkdir /home/groupspace</i>\n"
"# <i>chgrp mygroup /home/groupspace</i>\n"
"# <i>chmod g+s /home/groupspace</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1207
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, any users in the group mygroup can create files or directories inside\n"
"<path>/home/groupspace</path>, and they will be automatically assigned a group\n"
"ownership of mygroup as well. Depending on the users' umask setting, new\n"
"filesystem objects may or may not be readable, writable, or executable by other\n"
"members of the mygroup group.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1217
#, no-wrap
msgid "Directories and deletion"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1221
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"By default, Linux directories behave in a way that may not be ideal in all\n"
"situations. Normally, anyone can rename or delete a file inside a directory, as\n"
"long as they have write access to that directory. For directories used by\n"
"individual users, this behavior is usually just fine.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1228
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, for directories that are used by many users, especially\n"
"<path>/tmp</path> and <path>/var/tmp</path>, this behavior can be bad news.\n"
"Since anyone can write to these directories, anyone can delete or rename anyone\n"
"else's files -- even if they don't own them! Obviously, it's hard to use\n"
"<path>/tmp</path> for anything meaningful when any other user can type <c>rm\n"
"-rf /tmp/*</c> at any time and destroy everyone's files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1237
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Thankfully, Linux has something called the sticky bit. When <path>/tmp</path>\n"
"has the sticky bit set (with a <c>chmod +t</c>), the only people who are able\n"
"to delete or rename files in <path>/tmp</path> are the directory's owner\n"
"(typically root), the file's owner, or root. Virtually all Linux distributions\n"
"enable <path>/tmp</path>'s sticky bit by default, but you may find that the\n"
"sticky bit comes in handy in other situations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1248
