#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1332
#, no-wrap
msgid "Linux account managment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1334
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing /etc/passwd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1338
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this section, we'll look at the Linux account management mechanism, starting\n"
"with the <path>/etc/passwd</path> file, which defines all the users that exist\n"
"on a Linux system. You can view your own <path>/etc/passwd</path> file by\n"
"typing less <path>/etc/passwd</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1345
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Each line in <path>/etc/passwd</path> defines a user account. Here's an example\n"
"line from my <path>/etc/passwd</path> file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1349
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1561
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/passwd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1350
#, no-wrap
msgid "drobbins:x:1000:1000:Daniel Robbins:/home/drobbins:/bin/bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1354
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As you can see, there is quite a bit of information on this line. In fact, each\n"
"<path>/etc/passwd</path> line consists of multiple fields, each separated by a\n"
":.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1360
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The first field defines the username (drobbins)), and the second field contains\n"
"an x. On ancient Linux systems, this field contained an encrypted password to\n"
"be used for authentication, but virtually all Linux systems now store this\n"
"password information in another file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1367
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The third field (1000) defines the numeric user id associated with this\n"
"particular user, and the fourth field (1000) associates this user with a\n"
"particular group; in a few panels, we'll see where group 1000 is defined.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1373
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The fifth field contains a textual description of this account -- in this case,\n"
"the user's name. The sixth field defines this user's home directory, and the\n"
"seventh field specifies the user's default shell -- the one that will be\n"
"automatically started when this user logs in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1382
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/passwd tips and tricks"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1386
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You've probably noticed that there are many more user accounts defined in\n"
"<path>/etc/passwd</path> than actually log in to your system. This is because\n"
"various Linux components use user accounts to enhance security. Typically,\n"
"these system accounts have a user id (\"uid\") of under 100, and many of them\n"
"will have something like /bin/false listed as a default shell. Since the\n"
"<path>/bin/false</path> program does nothing but exit with an error code, this\n"
"effectively prevents these accounts from being used as login accounts -- they\n"
"are for internal use only.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1399
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1410
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1590
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/shadow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1403
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So, user accounts themselves are defined in <path>/etc/passwd</path>. Linux\n"
"systems contain a companion file to <path>/etc/passwd</path> that's called\n"
"<path>/etc/shadow</path>. This file, unlike <path>/etc/passwd</path>, is\n"
"readable only by root and contains encrypted password information. Let's look\n"
"at a sample line from <path>/etc/shadow</path>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1411
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1591
#, no-wrap
msgid "drobbins:$1$1234567890123456789012345678901:11664:0:-1:-1:-1:-1:0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1415
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Each line defines password information for a particular account, and again,\n"
"each field is separated by a :. The first field defines the particular user\n"
"account with which this shadow entry is associated. The second field contains\n"
"an encrypted password. The remaining fields are described in the following\n"
"table:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1424
#, no-wrap
msgid "field 3"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1425
#, no-wrap
msgid "# of days since 1/1/1970 that the password was modified"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1428
#, no-wrap
msgid "field 4"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1430
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # of days before password will be allowed to be changed (0 for \"change\n"
"    anytime\")\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1435
#, no-wrap
msgid "field 5"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1437
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # of days before system will force user to change to a new password (-1\n"
"    for \"never\")\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1442
#, no-wrap
msgid "field 6"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1444
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # of days before password expires that user will be warned about\n"
"    expiration (-1 for \"no warning\")\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1449
#, no-wrap
msgid "field 7"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1451
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # of days after password expiration that this account is automatically\n"
"    # disabled by the system (-1 for \"never disable\")\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1456
#, no-wrap
msgid "field 8"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1458
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # of days that this account has been disabled (-1 for \"this account is\n"
"    enabled\")\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1463
#, no-wrap
msgid "field 9"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1464
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reserved for future use"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1471
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1479
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/group"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1475
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Next, we take a look at the <path>/etc/group</path> file, which defines all the\n"
"groups on a Linux system. Here's a sample line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1480
#, no-wrap
msgid "drobbins:x:1000:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1484
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <path>/etc/group</path> field format is as follows. The first field defines\n"
"the name of the group; the second field is a vestigial password field that now\n"
"simply holds an x, and the third field defines the numeric group id of this\n"
"particular group. The fourth field (empty in the above example) defines any\n"
"users that are members of this group.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1492
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You'll recall that our sample <path>/etc/passwd</path> line referenced a group\n"
"id of 1000. This has the effect of placing the drobbins user in the drobbins\n"
"group, even though the drobbins username isn't listed in the fourth field of\n"
"<path>/etc/group</path>. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1501
#, no-wrap
msgid "Group notes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1505
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A note about associating users with groups: on some systems, you'll find that\n"
"every new login account is associated with an identically named (and usually\n"
"identically numbered) group. On other systems, all login accounts will belong\n"
"to a single users group. The approach that you use on the system(s) you\n"
"administrate is up to you. Creating matching groups for each user has the\n"
"advantage of allowing users to more easily control access to their own files by\n"
"placing trusted friends in their personal group.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1517
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding a user and group by hand"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1521
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, I'll show you how to create your own user and group account. The best way\n"
"to learn how to do this is to add a new user to the system manually. To begin,\n"
"first make sure that your EDITOR environment variable is set to your favorite\n"
"text editor:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1527
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking favorite text editor variable"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1528
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>echo $EDITOR</i>\n"
"vim\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1533
#, no-wrap
msgid "If it isn't, you can set EDITOR by typing something like:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1536
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting EDITOR variable"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1537
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>export EDITOR=/usr/bin/emacs</i>\n"
"# <i>vipw</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1542
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You should now find yourself in your favorite text editor with the\n"
"<path>/etc/passwd</path> file loaded up on the screen. When modifying system\n"
"<path>passwd</path> and <path>group</path> files, it's very important to use\n"
"the <c>vipw</c> and <c>vigr</c> commands. They take extra precautions to ensure\n"
"that your critical <path>passwd</path> and <path>group</path> files are locked\n"
"properly so they don't become corrupted.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1553
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing /etc/passwd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1557
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that you have the <path>/etc/passwd</path> file up, go ahead and add the\n"
"following line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1562
#, no-wrap
msgid "testuser:x:3000:3000:LPI tutorial test user:/home/testuser:/bin/false\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1566
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We've just added a \"testuser\" user with a UID of 3000. We've added him to a\n"
"group with a GID of 3000, which we haven't created just yet. Alternatively, we\n"
"could have assigned this user to the GID of the users group if we wanted. This\n"
"new user has a comment that reads LPI tutorial test user; the user's home\n"
"directory is set to <path>/home/testuser</path>, and the user's shell is set to\n"
"<path>/bin/false</path> for security purposes. If we were creating an non-test\n"
"account, we would set the shell to <path>/bin/bash</path>. OK, go ahead and\n"
"save your changes and exit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1579
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing /etc/shadow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1583
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, we need to add an entry in <path>/etc/shadow</path> for this particular\n"
"user. To do this, type <c>vipw -s</c>. You'll be greeted with your favorite\n"
"editor, which now contains the <path>/etc/shadow</path> file. Now, go ahead and\n"
"copy the line of an existing user account (one that has a password and is\n"
"longer than the standard system account entries):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1595
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, change the username on the copied line to the name of your new user, and\n"
"ensure that all fields (particularly the password aging ones) are set to your\n"
"liking:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1600
#, no-wrap
msgid "Modifed /etc/shadow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1601
#, no-wrap
msgid "testuser:$1$1234567890123456789012345678901:11664:0:-1:-1:-1:-1:0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1605
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now, save and exit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1611
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting a password"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1615
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You'll be back at the prompt. Now, it's time to set a password for your new\n"
"user:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1619
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting password for new user"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1620
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>passwd testuser</i>\n"
"Enter new UNIX password: <comment>(enter a password for testuser)</comment>\n"
"Retype new UNIX password: <comment>(enter testuser's new password again)</comment>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1628
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing /etc/group"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1632
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that <path>/etc/passwd</path> and <path>/etc/shadow</path> are set up, it's\n"
"now time to get <path>/etc/group</path> configured properly. To do this, type:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1636
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring /etc/group"
msgstr ""

