#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1684
#, no-wrap
msgid "Account admin utils"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1688
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that you know how to add a new account and group by hand, let's review the\n"
"various time-saving account administration utilities available under Linux. Due\n"
"to space constraints, we won't cover a lot of detail describing these commands.\n"
"Remember that you can always get more information about a command by viewing\n"
"the command's man page. If you are planning to take the LPIC 101 exam, you\n"
"should spend some time getting familiar with each of these commands.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1697
#, no-wrap
msgid "newgrp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1701
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"By default, any files that a user creates are assigned to the user's group\n"
"specified in <path>/etc/passwd</path>. If the user belongs to other groups, he\n"
"or she can type newgrp thisgroup to set current default group membership to the\n"
"group thisgroup. Then, any new files created will inherit thisgroup membership.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1709
#, no-wrap
msgid "<c>chage</c>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1711
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    The <c>chage</c> command is used to view and change the password aging\n"
"    setting stored in <path>/etc/shadow</path>.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1716
#, no-wrap
msgid "<c>gpasswd</c>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1717
#, no-wrap
msgid "A general-purpose group administration tool."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1720
#, no-wrap
msgid "<c>groupadd</c>/<c>groupdel</c>/<c>groupmod</c>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1721
#, no-wrap
msgid "Used to add/delete/modify groups in <path>/etc/group</path>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1724
#, no-wrap
msgid "<c>useradd</c>/<c>userdel</c>/<c>usermod</c>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1726
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Used to add/delete/modify users in <path>/etc/passwd</path>. These commands\n"
"    also perform various other convenience functions. See the man pages for\n"
"    more information.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1732
#, no-wrap
msgid "<c>pwconv</c>/<c>grpconv</c>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1734
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Used to convert <path>passwd</path> and <path>group</path> files to\n"
"    \"new-style\" shadow passwords.  Virtually all Linux systems already use\n"
"    shadow passwords, so you should never need to use these commands.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1746
#, no-wrap
msgid "Tuning the user environment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1748
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introducing \"fortune\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1752
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Your shell has many useful options that you can set to fit your personal\n"
"preferences. So far, however, we haven't discussed any way to have these\n"
"settings set up automatically every time you log in, except for re-typing them\n"
"each time. In this section we will look at tuning your login environment by\n"
"modifying startup files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1760
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"First, let's add a friendly message for when you first log in. To see an\n"
"example message, run <c>fortune</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1764
#, no-wrap
msgid "Running fortune command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1765
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>fortune</i>\n"
"No amount of careful planning will ever replace dumb luck.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1772
#, no-wrap
msgid ".bash_profile"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1776
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, let's set up <c>fortune</c> so that it gets run every time you log in. Use\n"
"your favorite text editor to edit a file named <path>.bash_profile</path> in\n"
"your home directory. If the file doesn't exist already, go ahead and create it.\n"
"Insert a line at the top:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1782
#, no-wrap
msgid "~/.bash_profile"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1783
#, no-wrap
msgid "fortune\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1787
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Try logging out and back in. Unless you're running a display manager like xdm,\n"
"gdm, or kdm, you should be greeted cheerfully when you log in:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1791
#, no-wrap
msgid "Results of fortune command in .bash_profile file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1792
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mycroft.flatmonk.org login: chouser\n"
"Password:\n"
"Freedom from incrustations of grime is contiguous to rectitude.\n"
"$\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1801
#, no-wrap
msgid "The login shell"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1805
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When bash started, it walked through the <path>.bash_profile</path> file in\n"
"your home directory, running each line as though it had been typed at a bash\n"
"prompt. This is called sourcing the file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1811
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Bash acts somewhat differently depending on how it is started. If it is started\n"
"as a login shell, it will act as it did above -- first sourcing the system-wide\n"
"<path>/etc/profile</path>, and then your personal <path>~/.bash_profile</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1817
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are two ways to tell bash to run as a login shell. One way is used when\n"
"you first log in: bash is started with a process name of -bash. You can see\n"
"this in your process listing:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1822
#, no-wrap
msgid "Process listing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1823
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>ps u</i>\n"
"USER       PID %CPU %MEM   VSZ  RSS TTY      STAT START   TIME COMMAND\n"
"chouser    404  0.0  0.0  2508  156 tty2     S     2001   0:00 -bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1829
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You will probably see a much longer listing, but you should have at least one\n"
"COMMAND with a dash before the name of your shell, like -bash in the example\n"
"above. This dash is used by the shell to determine if it's being run as a login\n"
"shell.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1838
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding --login"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1842
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The second way to tell bash to run as a login shell is with the <c>--login</c>\n"
"command-line option. This is sometimes used by terminal emulators (like xterm)\n"
"to make their bash sessions act like initial login sessions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1848
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"After you have logged in, more copies of your shell will be run. Unless they\n"
"are started with <c>--login</c> or have a dash in the process name, these\n"
"sessions will not be login shells. If they give you a prompt, however, they are\n"
"called interactive shells. If bash is started as interactive, but not login, it\n"
"will ignore <path>/etc/profile</path> and <path>~/.bash_profile</path> and will\n"
"instead source <path>~/.bashrc</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><th>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1858
#, no-wrap
msgid "interactive"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><th>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1859
#, no-wrap
msgid "login"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><th>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1860
#, no-wrap
msgid "profile"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><th>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1861
#, no-wrap
msgid "rc"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1864
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1865
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1870
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1877
#, no-wrap
msgid "yes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1866
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1873
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1878
#, no-wrap
msgid "source"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1867
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1872
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1879
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1884
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1885
#, no-wrap
msgid "ignore"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><table><tr><ti>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1871
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1876
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1882
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1883
#, no-wrap
msgid "no"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1892
#, no-wrap
msgid "Testing for interactivity"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1896
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Sometimes bash sources your <path>~/.bashrc</path>, even though it isn't really\n"
"interactive, such as when using commands like rsh and scp. This is important to\n"
"keep in mind because printing out text, like we did with the fortune command\n"
"earlier, can really mess up these non-interactive bash sessions. It's a good\n"
"idea to use the PS1 variable to detect whether the current shell is truly\n"
"interactive before printing text from a startup file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1904
#, no-wrap
msgid "Testing PS1 varibale"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1905
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"if [ -n \"$PS1\" ]; then\n"
"fortune\n"
"fi\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1913
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/profile and /etc/skel"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1917
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As a system administrator, you are in charge of <path>/etc/profile</path>.\n"
"Since it is sourced by everyone when they first log in, it is important to keep\n"
"it in working order. It is also a powerful tool in making things work correctly\n"
"for new users as soon as they log into their new account.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1924
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"However, there are some settings that you may want new users to have as\n"
"defaults, but also allow them to change easily. This is where the\n"
"<path>/etc/skel</path> directory comes in. When you use the <c>useradd</c>\n"
"command to create a new user account, it copies all the files from\n"
"<path>/etc/skel</path> into the user's new home directory. That means you can\n"
"put helpful <path>.bash_profile</path> and <path>.bashrc</path> files in\n"
"<path>/etc/skel</path> to get new users off to a good start.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1936
#, no-wrap
msgid "export"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1940
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Variables in bash can be marked so that they are set the same in any new shells\n"
"that it starts; this is called being marked for export. You can have bash list\n"
"all of the variables that are currently marked for export in your shell\n"
"session:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1946
#, no-wrap
msgid "results of export command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1947
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>export</i>\n"
"declare -x EDITOR=\"vim\"\n"
"declare -x HOME=\"/home/chouser\"\n"
"declare -x MAIL=\"/var/spool/mail/chouser\"\n"
"declare -x PAGER=\"/usr/bin/less\"\n"
"declare -x PATH=\"/bin:/usr/bin:/usr/local/bin:/home/chouser/bin\"\n"
"declare -x PWD=\"/home/chouser\"\n"
"declare -x TERM=\"xterm\"\n"
"declare -x USER=\"chouser\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1961
#, no-wrap
msgid "Marking variables for export"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1965
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If a variable is not marked for export, any new shells that it starts will not\n"
"have that variable set. However, you can mark a variable for export by passing\n"
"it to the <c>export</c> built-in:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1970
#, no-wrap
msgid "Marking variable for export"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1971
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>FOO=foo</i>\n"
"$ <i>BAR=bar</i>\n"
"$ <i>export BAR</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo $FOO $BAR</i>\n"
"foo bar\n"
"$ <i>bash</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo $FOO $BAR</i>\n"
"bar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1982
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this example, the variables FOO and BAR were both set, but only BAR was\n"
"marked for export. When a new bash was started, it had lost the value for FOO.\n"
"If you exit this new bash, you can see that the original one still has values\n"
"for both FOO and BAR:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1988
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking settings in original bash"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1989
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>exit</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo $FOO $BAR</i>\n"
"foo bar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:1997
#, no-wrap
msgid "Export and set -x"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2001
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Because of this behavior, variables can be set in <path>~/.bash_profile</path>\n"
"or <path>/etc/profile</path> and marked for export, and then never need to be\n"
"set again. There are some options that cannot be exported, however, and so they\n"
"must be put in put in your <path>~/.bashrc</path> and your <e>profile</e> in\n"
"order to be set consistently. These options are adjusted with the set built-in:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2008
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using set command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2009
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ <i>set -x</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2013
#, no-wrap
msgid "The <c>-x</c> option causes bash to print out each command it is about to run:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2016
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking results of -x option"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2017
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>echo $FOO</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo foo</i>\n"
"foo\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2023
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This can be very useful for understanding unexpected quoting behavior or\n"
"similar strangeness. To turn off the <c>-x</c> option, do <c>set +x</c>. See\n"
"the bash man page for all of the options to the set built-in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2031
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting variables with \"set\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2035
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>set</c> built-in can also be used for setting variables, but when used\n"
"that way, it is optional. The bash command <c>set FOO=foo</c> means exactly the\n"
"same as <c>FOO=foo</c>. Un-setting a variable is done with the <c>unset</c>\n"
"built-in:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2041
#, no-wrap
msgid "Un-setting variable"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2042
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>FOO=bar</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo $FOO</i>\n"
"bar\n"
"$ <i>unset FOO</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo $FOO</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2052
#, no-wrap
msgid "Unset vs. FOO="
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2056
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This is <e>not</e> the same as setting a variable to nothing, although it is\n"
"sometimes hard to tell the difference. One way to tell is to use the <c>set</c>\n"
"built-in with no parameters to list all current variables:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2061
#, no-wrap
msgid "Comparison of unset and FOO="
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2062
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>FOO=bar</i>\n"
"$ <i>set | grep ^FOO</i>\n"
"FOO=bar\n"
"$ <i>FOO=</i>\n"
"$ <i>set | grep ^FOO</i>\n"
"FOO=\n"
"$ <i>unset FOO</i>\n"
"$ <i>set | grep ^FOO</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2073
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Using <c>set</c> with no parameters like this is similar to using the\n"
"<c>export</c> built-in, except that <c>set</c> lists all variables instead of\n"
"just those marked for export.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2081
#, no-wrap
msgid "Exporting to change command behavior"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2085
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Often, the behavior of commands can be altered by setting environment\n"
"variables. Just as with new bash sessions, other programs that are started from\n"
"your bash prompt will only be able to see variables that are marked for export.\n"
"For example, the command <c>man</c> checks the variable PAGER to see what\n"
"program to use to step through the text one page at a time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2092
#, no-wrap
msgid "Exporting PAGER variable"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2093
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>PAGER=less</i>\n"
"$ <i>export PAGER</i>\n"
"$ <i>man man</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2099
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With PAGER set to <c>less</c>, you will see one page at a time, and pressing\n"
"the space bar moves on to the next page. If you change PAGER to <c>cat</c>, the\n"
"text will be displayed all at once, without stopping.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2104
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting PAGER variable to cat"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2105
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>PAGER=cat</i>\n"
"$ <i>man man</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2112
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using \"env\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2116
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, if you forget to set PAGER back to <c>less</c>, <c>man</c> (as\n"
"well as some other commands) will continue to display all their text without\n"
"stopping. If you wanted to have PAGER set to <c>cat</c> just once, you could\n"
"use the <c>env</c> command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2122
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using env command to set variable"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ <i>PAGER=less</i>\n"
"$ <i>env PAGER=cat man man</i>\n"
"$ <i>echo $PAGER</i>\n"
"less\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/lpi-101-intermediate-p3.xml:2130
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This time, PAGER was exported to <c>man</c> with a value of <c>cat</c>, but the\n"
"PAGER variable itself remained unchanged in the bash session.\n"
msgstr ""

